<Base title="About Peptide Atlas" description="How Peptide Atlas approaches clinic research, physician verification, educational reporting, and regulatory coverage." currentSection="">
  <article>
    <p class="eyebrow">About the project</p>
    <h1>Evidence first, with clear limits.</h1>
    <p>Peptide Atlas is an independent directory and editorial project for people researching peptide-related clinics, clinicians, regulation, and clinical evidence. It does not sell treatments, accept paid directory placement, or provide medical advice.</p>
    <h2>What we publish</h2>
    <p>Directory listings are built from clinic websites and official professional records. News and legal coverage must point to an authoritative primary source. Educational guides must cite at least two authoritative sources.</p>
    <h2>Who writes the material</h2>
    <p>Articles are prepared by the Peptide Atlas Editorial Team using a documented research workflow. Automated tools may assist with collection and drafting, but publication is subject to deterministic sourcing, verification, claim, and schema checks.</p>
    <h2>What we do not claim</h2>
    <p>A directory listing is not an endorsement. Verification means that specific facts were checked against the cited records at the time shown. It does not assess the quality, safety, or suitability of an individual treatment plan.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
